					<h3>About</h3>
					<p>Valerie has done a variety of work, both as a volunteer and as a paid employee. Her first job was at Mini Ivy Tutoring Center, where she tutored elementary and middle school students in math and English. In addition, she performed various office administrative duties, such as keeping track of attendance and picking up phone calls. </p>
					<p>In the summer of 2015, she participated in Girls Who Code’s Summer Immersion Program, where she was introduced to computer science. She learned how to code in JavaScript, Python, and HTML. Besides gaining technical skills, she was able to connect with female engineers and entrepreneurs, and hear their stories about what it’s like to work in a tech company. The program also gave her the opportunity to visit different tech companies, such as Google and Microsoft. For the final project, she created a user-friendly online app using HTML and JavaScript to locate and post about volunteer services.</p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<h3>Education</h3>
					<p>The easiest classes that Valerie has taken here at the University of Rochester are CSC170, PSY101 and CHI102. She was able to deepen her knowledge of creating and designing web pages with CSC170. The concepts in PSY101 were not difficult to understand and the mini courses throughout the semester made the class more interesting. CHI102 was not a difficult course, but it required a lot of work and practice every day to understand the vocabulary and grammar concepts.</p>
					<p>The harder classes include BIO110 and CHM131. For her, BIO110 was more difficult because it focused mainly on the molecular level of biology. CHM131 was fine until she started to learn about acids and titrations. Another class that was intense was MTH162. Even though the AP exam gave her a good foundation, a lot of the topics were difficult to understand, such as series.</p>
				</div>
				<div>
					<h3>Interests</h3>
					<p>In 2016, Valerie interned with the Committee Against Anti-Asian Violence’s Asian Youth in Action program. As an intern, she worked with the Chinatown Tenants Union to help tenants challenge evictions and harassment from their landlords. She also interpreted for rent stabilized tenants sharing their stories at hearings to fight for a rent freeze. Working at this organization allowed her to realize that striving for a collective goal is not only necessary, but can also make housing justice for low income residents a reality.</p>
					<p>For the past two years, Valerie has been an intern at the American Museum of Natural History’s ornithology department. She conducted library and laboratory research on the genetic diversity of European starlings. The goal of the project was to determine if there were any distinct genetic differences between the European starlings of North America and their parent population. The research included extracting DNA from the flesh of the bird specimens and amplifying mitochondrial DNA from the birds. In addition, she used a bioinformatics software called Geneious to analyze and edit the DNA sequences. The program culminated in a research presentation at a symposium session.</p>
